Public Prosecutor v Soh Han Seong
[2023] SGMC 4

Case Number:Magistrate Arrest Case No 900457 of 2020, Magistrate's Appeal No. 9099-2022-01
Decision Date:28 February 2023
Tribunal/Court:Magistrates Court
Coram: Brenda Tan
Counsel Name(s): Pavithra Ramkumar (Attorney General's Chambers) for the Public Prosecutor; Mr James Joseph (Prestige Legal LLP) for the accused.
Parties: Public Prosecutor — Soh Han Seong

Criminal Law – Offences – Property – Criminal misappropriation of property

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9099/2022/01.]

28 February 2023

District Judge Brenda Tan:

Introduction

1       The accused is Soh Han Seong (also known as Fernando Soh), a 46-year-old male Singaporean. He claimed trial to one charge under s 403 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed) of dishonestly misappropriating a sum of $20,000 belonging to PW2 Jessica Lee Khar Choo (“PW2 Jessica Lee”) which was deposited into his POSB bank account by withdrawing it for his own use. At the conclusion of the trial, I found the accused guilty as charged and I convicted him accordingly. I sentenced him to ten weeks’ imprisonment.

2       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision has appealed against his conviction and sentence. He is presently on bail pending appeal.

The charge

3       The charge that the accused claimed trial to read as follows:

(a)     MAC-900457-2020 (exhibit C1)

CHARGE (AMENDED)

You, are charged that you, between 4 and 5 October 2018, in Singapore, did dishonestly misappropriate to your own use a sum of S$20,000.00 belonging to one Jessica Lee Khar Choo, which was deposited into your POSB savings account XXX (“Account”), by withdrawing that sum of $20,000.00 in cash from your Account, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under section 403 Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed).

Undisputed facts

4       It was common ground that the accused and one Seah Keng Hoi Catherine (“Catherine Seah”) came to know each other around August[note: 1] or September[note: 2] 2018 when the accused who was working as a Ryde driver accepted her advance bookings through the Ryde application (“Ryde app”) to drive her to and fro from her home and the dialysis centre for her dialysis appointments. Catherine Seah lived at Blk 494E, #XXX, Tampines Street 43[note: 3] (“Catherine Seah’s home”). She had to go for dialysis three times a week usually from 12.30pm to 5pm[note: 4] at the dialysis centre located at Blk 102 Aljunied Crescent[note: 5] (“Dialysis Centre”). The accused told the court that he would fetch her at 11.30am every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday from her home to the Dialysis Centre and return at 4.30pm to send her home. He said that he became good friends with Catherine Seah after a few trips. In fact, Catherine Seah treated the accused as her “godson” and he called her “godmother” [note: 6].

5       It was not in dispute that sometime in September 2018, the accused agreed to help Catherine Seah receive $20,000 in his POSB savings account (“POSB account”) which he would then withdraw and pass it to her in cash. It was not in dispute either that PW2 Jessica Lee who did not know both Catherine Seah and the accused had deposited $20,000 into the accused’s POSB account on 4 October 2018. The accused admitted that he had received $20,000 in his POSB account on 4 October 2018[note: 7] and that he had gone to the ATM to withdraw the entire sum between 4 to 5 October 2018 over a few transactions[note: 8]. What was in dispute was whether the accused had subsequently handed over the cash of $20,000 (“the Money”) to Catherine Seah on 5 Oct 2018 as arranged.

The issue before the court

6       The Prosecution’s case was that Catherine Seah had arranged with the accused to pass her the Money at the Dialysis Centre on 5 October 2018, but the accused failed to show up and had instead retained the Money and misappropriated it for his own use.

7       The accused denied that he had kept the Money. He claimed that on 5 October 2018, he had re-arranged to meet Catherine Seah after her dialysis, at 5pm at the coffeeshop (“the Coffeeshop”) opposite her home and that he had handed her the Money there before she walked home. He maintained that there was no dishonest misappropriation.

8       Therefore, the central issue before the court was whether the accused had handed over the Money to Catherine Seah at 5pm on 5 October 2018 at the Coffeeshop[note: 9].

Pertinent facts to note

9       It would be pertinent to note from the outset that Catherine Seah passed away on 9 September 2019 at the age of 64 from ischemic heart disease before the trial commenced in October 2020[note: 10]. Hence, the Prosecution was relying on Catherine Seah’s police report lodged on 7 October 2018 and her statement to the police dated 11 October 2018 as part of its case. I had admitted both Catherine Seah’s police report (exhibit P3) and statement to the police (exhibit P5) in evidence pursuant to s 32(1)(j)(i) of the Evidence Act (Cap 97, 1997 Rev Ed) (“EA”) on the ground that Catherine Seah was dead and that the requirements in s 32 of the EA had been satisfied[note: 11]. The Defence conceded that it had no legal basis to object to the admissibility of Catherine Seah’s police report and statement[note: 12] rather it was a question of weight to be attached to her evidence.

10     Given Catherine Seah’s demise, the WhatsApp messages that she exchanged with the accused and the details of their call logs were consequently of significance in this trial.

11     As the accused claimed that he had met and passed the Money to Catherine Seah at 5pm at the Coffeeshop on 5 October 2018, the timing as to when Catherine Seah returned home after her dialysis that afternoon thus became critical. It was not in dispute that sometime in the afternoon, after her dialysis, she had hired a Ryde vehicle to bring her home from the Dialysis Centre by dropping her at Blk 494D, Tampines Street 43 (“Blk 494D”). The Defence accepted that the Police Camera (PolCam) CCTV footages captured Catherine Seah walking to the first floor of her lift lobby at Blk 494E on 5 October 2018 and entering the lift at 5.10pm alone[note: 13]. The Defence acknowledged that between 5.10pm and 8pm, the PolCam CCTV footages did not show Catherine Seah coming down by the lift or staircases to the first floor again as it did not challenge these footages[note: 14].

The Prosecution’s case

12     I set out below the material evidence that was adduced by the Prosecution.

Evidence of Catherine Seah (Deceased)

13     Catherine Seah’s evidence as encapsulated in her statement to the police in exhibit P5 may be summarized as follows. She was single and lived alone. Her highest educational background was “A” levels. She worked as a health supplement product advisor until she retired in 2015. Since then, she had been sick with kidney failure and was receiving financial assistance from the government.

14     She met one Harry Cheng on Facebook about three years ago (which would be 2015). He told her that he was from the United Kingdom and worked as a marine engineer. They had never met in person and communicated through WhatsApp. In 2017, she assisted Harry Cheng to receive a sum of $10,000 in her DBS bank account which caused her to be investigated by the police and as a result, her DBS bank account was frozen. The money was returned to the victim and the police issued Catherine Seah a stern warning not to receive such funds in the future. Notwithstanding, Catherine Seah continued to talk to Harry Cheng who showed her much love and concern because she had no one else to talk to.

15     Sometime in August or September 2018, Harry Cheng again asked Catherine Seah if he could borrow her bank account to receive funds. He told her that he was borrowing money from his friends and once the money was transferred to her, he would tell her what to do. He said that he was staying in Thailand and his daughter was in a boarding school and that he needed money. Catherine Seah was “love struck” by Harry Cheng[note: 15] so she agreed to help him.

16     As Catherine Seah’s bank accounts had all been frozen, she decided to ask the accused if he could help her to receive the funds. The accused finally agreed to help her and on 9 September 2018, he furnished his NRIC and POSB account numbers to Catherine Seah and in turn, she provided those details to Harry Cheng. In this regard, it was not in dispute that the accused addressed Harry Cheng as his “godpa”.

17     On 4 October 2018, Harry Cheng messaged Catherine Seah that $20,000 had been transferred into the accused’s POSB account. Catherine Seah then messaged the accused and asked him to withdraw the Money and pass it to her on 5 October 2018 at the Dialysis Centre at 12pm[note: 16]. The accused agreed to do so. Catherine Seah asked whether she could follow him to the bank, but he told her not to. The accused however, failed to turn up at the Dialysis Centre on 5 October 2018. Catherine Seah kept messaging him to ask him to hand over the Money, but he did not show up and thereafter he went missing. As such, on 10 October 2018, Catherine Seah went to lodge a police report that the accused had disappeared with the Money. In this regard, I noted that Catherine Seah had lodged the police report in exhibit P3 on 7 October 2018 and not on 10 October 2018 as she had mentioned in her statement.

18     Catherine Seah stated she was supposed to hand over the Money to an unknown person, but the plan did not take place since she did not receive the Money from the accused. Catherine Seah later learned from Harry Cheng’s friend called Tan Choo that one Jessica was the person who had transferred the Money into the accused’s POSB account[note: 17].

19     I noted that there were some discrepancies between Catherine Seah’s statement and her police report in exhibit P3 regarding the purpose for the Money. According to her police report, the Money was a loan from Harry Cheng’s friend called Tan Choo to help her with her medical expenses. I will deal with the discrepancies in due course.

Evidence of PW2 Jessica Lee (Victim)

20     PW2 Jessica Lee testified that she got to know one Allen YuWong on Twos website and they became chat companions on WhatsApp[note: 18]. They had not met in person. Allen YuWong told her that he had a piece of property in California which he had sold but the US government would only release the sale proceeds to him after he had paid off the property tax. He asked PW2 Jessica Lee to help him pay his property tax by transferring S$20,000 to the US tax agent/officer’s account. He then provided PW2 Jessica Lee with the accused’s name and POSB account number which Allen YuWong had obtained from another person.

21     Believing that the accused was a tax officer, on 4 October 2018, PW2 Jessica Lee transferred the Money being her own money to the accused’s POSB account. She later learned from Allen YuWong that “the other party did not receive the money”[note: 19] and he advised her to lodge a police report.

22     On 5 October 2018 at 7.25pm, PW2 Jessica Lee lodged a police report (exhibit P1) stating that she had gone to the DBS Bank at Toa Payoh Hub on 4 October 2018 at about 12.53pm to deposit $20,000 into the accused’s POSB account. Thereafter she found the situation suspicious and contacted Allen YuWong who assured her that he did not withdraw the Money and told her not to worry. In her police report, PW2 Jessica Lee also stated that she went back to the DBS Bank at Toa Payoh to ask for assistance regarding the Money that she had transferred into the accused’s POSB account, but the counter staff told her to report to the police.

23     PW2 had no idea what had happened to the Money. She did not know the accused, had not met him nor communicated with him before. She also did not know who Catherine Seah was.

Evidence of PW3 Mohamad Pauzi Bin Ali (DBS bank representative)

24     PW3 Mohamad Pauzi Bin Ali (“PW3 Mohamad Pauzi”) was the assistant vice president of DBS Bank Singapore. The accused’s DBS bank statements for the period 4 October 2018 to 6 October 2018 was admitted in evidence as exhibit P2 through PW3 Mohamad Pauzi. The Defence did not dispute the transactions reflected in exhibit P2.

25     Exhibit P2 showed that after PW2 Jessica Lee had deposited the sum of $20,000 into the accused’s POSB account on 4 October 2018, there were three ATM withdrawals on the same day at “Sims Avenue Br3” in the respective amounts of $2,000, $2,000, and $1,000 totaling $5,000. The balance of $15,000 was withdrawn the next day on 5 October 2018. Exhibit P2 showed that there were six ATM withdrawals on 5 October 2018. Four withdrawals of $2,000 each were made at the ATM at “Sims Ave BR2” while the remaining two withdrawals of $5,000 and $3,000 were made at the ATM at “Pz S’pura BR2”. The ATM withdrawals on 5 October 2018 added up to $16,000. In total, $21,000 was withdrawn from the accused’s POSB account between 4 and 5 October 2018 after PW2 Jessica Lee had deposited the Money into his account.

Evidence of PW4 Muhammad Syarafuddin Bin Shariff (Police officer)

26     PW4 Sergeant Muhammad Syarafuddin Bin Shariff (“PW4 Sgt Muhammad Syarafuddin”) testified that he recorded Catherine Seah’s police report in exhibit P3 on 7 October 2018 at 1.36pm accurately. He clarified that according to Catherine Seah, she was to borrow a sum of $20,000 from Tan Choo[note: 20].

Evidence of PW5 Lee Choon Hua (Ryde driver)

27     PW5 Lee Choon Hua testified that in 2018 he was working as a Ryde driver, and he also delivered Tiger Beer in the morning. He was the Ryde driver who fetched Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018 from 105 Aljunied Crescent to Blk 494D. According to exhibit P4, a screenshot of the trip details retrieved from the Ryde app from his handphone, the journey commenced at 4:50pm and ended at 5:09pm. PW5 Lee Choon Hua did not know Catherine Seah, and this was the first time he had fetched her. He did not know the accused either.

Evidence of PW6 Manivannan S/O Kantasamy (Recording officer of Catherine Seah’s statement)

28     PW6 Station Inspector Manivannan S/O Kantasamy (“PW6 SI Manivannan”) was the police officer who recorded Catherine Seah’s statement in exhibit P5 on 11 October 2018. He confirmed that Catherine Seah gave the statement voluntarily and that he recorded it accurately.

29     PW6 SI Manivannan testified that on 12 October 2018, he, and his colleague PW7 Senior Staff Sergeant Hafit Ismail (“PW7 Sr SSgt Hafit”) left their office at 1pm to proceed to Catherine Seah’s residential block to verify whether there was any CCTV footage which might have captured the accused handing over the Money to Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018. They arrived at about 2pm whereupon they activated the Crime Strike Force personnel who were the officers managing the PolCam installed at the lift lobbies.

30     PW6 SI Manivannan told the court that there was only one lift lobby with two lifts and three sets of staircases at Catherine Seah’s block. PW6 SI Manivannan and PW7 Sr SS Hafit together with the Crime Strike Force officers watched the CCTV footages recorded by the Polcams at Catherine Seah’s block on 5 October 2018 between 5pm to 8pm.

31     From the CCTV footage of the lift lobby, PW6 SI Manivannan spotted Catherine Seah coming home alone at 5.10pm and entering the lift on the first level to go up to her unit. From the time Catherine Seah took the lift at 5.10pm until 8pm on 5 October 2018, the CCTV footages of the lift lobby and staircase landings did not show her coming downstairs again either by the lift or staircases[note: 21].

32     PW6 SI Manivannan used his own handphone to video record the footage of Catherine Seah arriving at her lift lobby at Blk 494E at 5.10pm and taking the lift. He was able to recognize Catherine Seah as he had just recorded her statement in exhibit P5 the day before. The brief video as recorded by PW6 SI Manivannan on his handphone was admitted in evidence as exhibit P6. PW6 SI Manivannan’s investigation diary dated 15 October 2018 where he made entries of what he did in relation to this case on 12 October 2018 from 1pm until 2.42pm was admitted in evidence as P7. Exhibit P7 supported PW6 SI Manivannan’s oral testimony.

Evidence of PW7 Hafit Ismail (Police officer)

33     PW7 Sr SSgt Hafit testified that his role in this case was to assist to watch the PolCam CCTV footages with PW6 SI Manivannan to ascertain whether Catherine Seah left her residence again after returning home on 5 October 2018. He told the court that there were four PolCams installed at Catherine Seah’s block, one at the lift lobby and the other three cameras at the staircase landings[note: 22]. From the CCTV footages, he saw Catherine Seah entering the lift at 5 plus pm and until 8pm, he did not see Catherine Seah coming down again.

Evidence of PW8 Muhammad Ashari Bin Adnan (forensic examiner)

34     PW8 Muhammad Ashari Bin Adnana (“PW8 Ashari”) was a forensic examiner attached to the Technology Crime Forensic Branch (TCFB) of the Criminal Investigation Department[note: 23]. On 2 October 2020, together with the Investigation Officer PW9 Staff Sergeant Muhd Zulkifli Bin Rahmat, they commenced a search for the digital contents of the accused’s handphone (exhibit P8).

35     PW8 Ashari’s evidence was not contested. The material evidence adduced from him was that he conducted a physical examination of the accused’s handphone and found that it contained one SIM card and one SD card. On the instructions of the Investigation Officer PW9, PW8 Ashari exported 621 call logs and 971 WhatsApp messages retrieved from the accused’s handphone which were related to the present case and saved them respectively in Annexes A and B to exhibit P9.

36     The call logs extracted were for the period 1st October to 11th October 2018. The WhatsApp messages extracted contained three types of chats. Chat number 1 consisted of messages between the accused and one overseas number “61XXX”[note: 24] where the person identified himself/herself as “Tan Choo”. Chat number 2 consisted of messages between the accused and Catherine Seah which the accused had deleted from his handphone but which PW8 Ashari managed to recover[note: 25]. Chat number 3 comprised the messages between the accused and Catherine Seah for the period 31 August 2018 and 10 October 2018 which were not deleted[note: 26].

Evidence of PW9 Muhd Zulkifli Bin Rahmat (Investigation Officer)

37     PW9 Staff Sergeant Muhd Zulkifli Bin Rahmat (“PW9 IO Zulkifli”), attached to the Commercial Affairs Department, was the Investigation Officer of this case. On 8 October 2018, he ordered the accused’s POSB account to be frozen[note: 27]. He obtained concurrence from the Attorney General’s Chambers in October 2019 to charge Catherine Seah for her role as a mule in money laundering under s 44 of the Corruption, Drug Trafficking and Other Serious Crimes (Confiscation of Benefits) Act in connection with this case[note: 28]. He was trying to contact Catherine Seah to serve the charge on her but learned in February 2020 that Catherine Seah had passed away. As for Tan Choo, Harry Cheng and Allen YuWong, PW9 IO Zulkifli had not been able to establish their identities[note: 29].

The Defence’s case

Evidence of DW1, the accused

38     The accused was unemployed. In 2018 he was working as a Ryde driver. He came to know Catherine Seah in early September 2018 after Catherine Seah made an advance booking through the Ryde app for the purpose of fetching her to the Dialysis Centre in the morning and bringing her home in the afternoon. He would ferry her three times a week, every Monday, Wednesday, and Friday at 11.30am for her dialysis and send her back at 4.30pm.

39     The accused and Catherine Seah became good friends after a few trips. Sometimes she would pay for his car rental and petrol expenses or even buy lunch or dinner for him. There were two other Ryde drivers which Catherine Seah would hire if the accused was not available. The accused knew the drivers to be one Ah Hua and one Allen. Most of the time Allen would be the backup driver. The accused did not know who Ah Hua was, but he suspected that Ah Hua was PW5 Lee Choon Hua because Ah Hua was also a part-time beer delivery driver like PW5 Lee Choon Hua.

40     Catherine Seah told the accused that her overseas boyfriend, Harry, needed to transfer a sum of money and asked if she could use the accused’s bank account. The accused agreed and gave Catherine Seah his POSB account number in late September 2018. On 4 October 2018, Catherine Seah called him to tell him that the Money had been transferred into his POSB account and she requested him to withdraw the Money in $100 denomination and pass it to her the next day. On 5 October 2018, the accused went to withdraw $20,000 from his POSB account. He then called Catherine Seah to tell her that he had withdrawn the Money whereupon Catherine Seah requested the accused to open another bank account at UOB because she said that Harry was going to transfer another $80,000 into the UOB bank account (“UOB account”). The accused said that he refused and told Catherine Seah that his UOB account had been frozen. He decided not to help Catherine Seah anymore as he felt suspicious.

41     The accused said that he had “a lot of conversation on message and log call” with Catherine Seah in the morning of 5 October 2018. After he messaged Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018 to say that he had withdrawn all the money and “See you at 5” at 11:30:52am[note: 30] to pass her the Money, there was no “communication” between them from 2pm to 8pm on 5 October 2018[note: 31]. On 5 October 2018, he met Catherine Seah between 5pm to 6pm at the Coffeeshop which was just a walking distance opposite her home and passed her the Money in an envelope. In this regard, the Defence later clarified that its case was that the accused had handed the Money to Catherine Seah at 5pm at the Coffeeshop[note: 32].

42     On 6 October 2018, Catherine Seah messaged the accused at 4:46:01pm and told him that she had packed Indian rojak for dinner which she could not finish. She invited the accused to fetch her for a hot drink at “ko fu” where she would share her food with him[note: 33]. The accused however did not meet Catherine Seah as he was angry with her. At 7:11:55pm, she messaged him again where she urged him to come to her place now so that they could go to “ko fu” to eat Indian rojak[note: 34]. But the accused did not go to meet her. At 9:09:12pm, Catherine Seah messaged the accused to say, “if u get me into the picture then u will be charge for money laundry”[note: 35]. The accused said that by this message, Catherine Seah wanted him to give a false statement to the investigation officer that the money was from Tan Choo, and it was not money laundering, in the event he was called up for investigations. At 9:10:45pm, Catherine Seah messaged the accused again to say, “I suggest u said Tan Choo is your friend N owed you money N its only right that u collect money from him”[note: 36]. The accused said that by this message, Catherine Seah wanted him to lie to the police that Tan Choo was his friend who owed him money and that Tan Choo was returning the accused the sum of $20,000 into the accused’s POSB account.

43     The accused further testified that he had been a Ryde driver for about a year. He explained that Ryde was a carpooling company unlike Grab which was a private hire ride company. According to the accused, LTA allowed Ryde drivers to carpool two trips a day with customers who were going to the same destination as the driver[note: 37]. Hence, all Ryde bookings had to be made in advance and they were not allowed to accept immediate bookings. The accused said advance bookings must be made at least half an hour in advance[note: 38].

44     During PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s cross-examination, he said that Catherine Seah had made the booking at 4.50pm and that he had arrived at her location at 4.51pm. The accused told the court that the Ryde app did not accept immediate bookings because they were against LTA rules and the company would get penalized and the driver could get his driving licence revoked. He therefore disagreed with PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence regarding Catherine Seah’s booking time and his arrival time at the Dialysis Centre.

45     The accused explained that he was Catherine Seah’s regular driver for about three months, so he understood her bookings very well. He knew that her dialysis would normally finish at 4.15pm after which she would wait outside at the shelter for her Ryde transport. She would ask her Ryde driver to send her to the Coffeeshop to let buy her dinner and she would buy dinner for the driver too. At times she would walk home from the Coffeeshop which was just opposite her block. The accused told the court that Catherine Seah was nice to the Ryde drivers specially to him as she would buy him and Ah Hua dinner.

46     In respect of Catherine Seah’s trip details in exhibit P4 which showed that her trip started at 4.50pm on 5 October 20180, the accused testified that since Ryde was based on carpooling, there was no need to pick the passenger at the exact time stated at 4.50pm. The driver could fetch Catherine Seah earlier than 4.50pm, like he would normally pick her at 4.30pm. He stated that occasionally he would accompany Catherine Seah for her dialysis after he sent her to the Dialysis Centre in the morning. In that case, he would send her home around 4.20pm since her dialysis would end at 4.15pm.

47     The accused told the court that Catherine Seah’s bookings were all made in advance. She would call her driver beforehand and book directly in the driver’s personal account in Ryde. He said that Catherine Seah preferred advanced bookings with regular drivers because she would be very tried after her dialysis and did not want to have to wait for the driver.

48     The accused totally disagreed with the evidence that PW5 Lee Choon Hua gave during his cross-examination that Catherine Seah had made the booking at 4.50pm and that PW5 Lee Choon Hua had fetched her at 4.51pm. In the experience of the accused, the journey from the Dialysis Centre to Blk 494D would take 20 to 25 minutes if they did not stop at the Coffeeshop to buy dinner due to heavy traffic. Catherine Seah was someone who talked a lot and they would engage in conversations during the journey. The accused estimated that PW5 Lee Choon Hua would have fetched Catherine Seah from the Dialysis Centre at 4.30pm to 4.35pm and she should have arrived at the Coffeeshop at 4.50pm. The accused said that Catherine Seah usually carried many bags with heavy things. It would take her three to five minutes from the time the vehicle reached Blk 494D for her to gather her bags, chat for a while before she would alight and walk to her lift lobby.

49     The accused said that even though the trip details in exhibit P4 showed that the booking was made for 4.50pm, Catherine Seah’s regular Ryde drivers could still fetch her earlier at 4.30pm, 4.35pm or 4.40pm because they knew that she finished her dialysis at 4.15pm and that she would be waiting at the shelter for her transport. So, they would normally pick her at 4.30pm although they would not be able to log the trip yet on the Ryde app since the booking was scheduled for 4.50pm. If they were to reach her place before the booking time of 4.50pm, they would wait until 4.50pm to log “pick-up” on the Ryde app and one minute later, they would log “drop off” so that they could collect payment for the trip from Ryde.

50     The accused told the court that Ryde would take 5% service fee from the carpooling fares. The accused pointed out that the trip details in exhibit P4 showed that Ryde had paid $8.55 into PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s “wallet” after deducting $0.45. This meant that PW5 Lee Choon Hua would have pressed “drop off” at 5.09pm because the payment of $8.55 was clocked at 5.09pm. Therefore, it did not mean that Catherine Seah alighted at 5.09pm but 5.09pm was the time that Ryde paid PW5 Lee Choon Hua $8.55 for the trip after he had pressed “drop off”. The accused said that Ryde would take three to five minutes to do the computation. Hence, based on the processing time and payment time of 5.09pm, Catherine Seah was most probably dropped off before 5pm on 5 October 2018[note: 39].

The court’s findings

51     After a careful evaluation of the evidence, I found that the accused did not hand over the Money to Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018 at 5pm at the Coffeeshop as he had claimed. In fact, he did not meet her on 5 October 2018 at all. My reasons were as follows.

From the messages exchanged between Catherine Seah and the accused on 4 and 5 October, the Dialysis Centre was the agreed meeting place and not the Coffeeshop

52     Catherine Seah and the accused exchanged numerous WhatsApp messages between 4 October 2018 and 5 October 2018 regarding the Money. The conversation started on 4 October 2018 between 4:24:42pm to 4.31:42pm when Catherine Seah informed the accused that the Money had been deposited into his POSB account and requested that he withdraw the Money “tomorrow morning” in $100 notes and pass the Money to her in an envelope at Aljunied Crescent Dialysis Centre[note: 40]. At 4:41:12pm, the accused replied “Ok”[note: 41]. About an hour later at 5.21.09pm, Catherine Seah reminded the accused to withdraw the Money “tomorrow” and give her the Money at “aljunied dc”[note: 42]. Again, the accused acknowledged “Ok” at 5:21:22pm[note: 43]. At 5:45:40pm, Catherine Seah told the accused that he could check his bank balance and see if the Money was in[note: 44]. At 7:46:30pm, she asked the accused if he needed her to go to the bank with him[note: 45]. The accused declined her offer by replying “no need” at 8:02:04pm and assured her at 8:02:19pm that he would “pass the money to (her) tomorrow”[note: 46]. Catherine Seah replied at 9:03:04pm, “see u tomorrow morning at dialysis centre” and the accused said “ok” at 9:22:30pm[note: 47].

53     From these messages on 4 October 2018, it was obvious that Catherine Seah and the accused had agreed that the accused would withdraw the Money in the morning on 5 October 2018 and pass it to Catherine Seah at the Dialysis Centre the same morning. It was noteworthy that during his cross-examination, the accused agreed that the plan was for him to pass Catherine Seah the Money at the Dialysis Centre, but he claimed that after he had withdrawn the Money on 5 October 2018, there was a change in the destination[note: 48].

54     The evidence did not support the accused’s contention. On the contrary, the messages on 5 October 2018 showed that Catherine Seah was waiting anxiously at the Dialysis Centre to receive the Money from the accused, and she was expecting him to pass it to her quickly. There was no mention in the messages between the accused and Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018 that the meeting place had been changed from the Dialysis Centre to the Coffeeshop.

55     The messages between Catherine Seah and the accused on 5 October 2018 from 11:29:58am to 1:48:33pm are tabulated below. The relevant messages have been highlighted. Catherine Seah and the accused did not exchange any messages after 1:48:33pm until 8:07:52pm. For completeness, I have included in the table, in a chronological order, details of the phone calls made between Catherine Seah and the accused[note: 49] and between Catherine Seah and Harry Cheng on 5 October 2018 up to 1:50pm[note: 50]. The phone calls have also been highlighted for easy reference.

56     As set out in the table above, on 5 October 2018, at 11:29:58am, Catherine Seah asked the accused, “r u coming now?” The accused replied with three messages between 11:30:26am to 11:30:52am, “No”, that he was “Otw to bank” and “See you at 5”[note: 51](“5pm message”). In the context of the messages on 4 and 5 October 2018, the arrangement was clearly for the accused to withdraw the Money in the morning on 5 October 2018 and pass it right away to Catherine Seah at the Dialysis Centre. Therefore, when the accused suddenly told Catherine Seah at 11:30:52am that he would see her at 5pm, in an attempt to delay the time for him to pass the Money to Catherine Seah, she swiftly responded at 11:32:06am and told the accused to “come earlier..”. She beseeched the accused repeatedly, at 11:36:49am, 11:50:16am, 11:52:52am and 12:17:51pm to go to the Dialysis Centre as soon as possible because his godpa was waiting for the money and even specified that she would be seated at “right hand side no. 15”. Despite her numerous requests, the accused admitted that he did not meet her at the Dialysis Centre.

57     In this regard, the accused claimed that Catherine Seah was merely hoping that he could go to the Dialysis Centre earlier to pass her the Money so that he could then accompany her throughout the dialysis and send her home. His assertion was plainly contradicted by the urgency in Catherine Seah’s messages on 5 October 2018 and the fact that there was no reference to the Coffeeshop in the messages.

“See you at 5” message on 5 October 2018 did not support the accused’s claim that the meeting place had been changed to the Coffeeshop

58     The accused told the court that the 5pm message proved that there was a change of plan and that he and Catherine Seah later agreed to meet at 5pm at the Coffeeshop for him to hand her the Money. The 5pm message clearly did not support the accused’s position. First, there was no mention of a different venue in the 5pm message. Secondly, there was no indication in the subsequent exchange between Catherine Seah and the accused that the meeting place had been changed to the Coffeeshop and the time deferred to 5pm.

59     The 5pm message was the only piece of evidence that the accused relied on during the trial to show that he had arranged to meet Catherine Seah at the Coffeeshop at 5pm where he claimed he then passed her the Money. When the accused realized belatedly at submissions stage that the 5pm message made no mention of the Coffeeshop, he then indicated through his counsel that he had called Catherine Seah at 12:40:20pm[note: 52](“12:40:20pm call”) on 5 October 2018 where they spoke for two minutes and 28 seconds and that was when he had conveyed the Coffeeshop location to her. This was clearly an afterthought and a crucial piece of evidence which he omitted to raise when he was on the witness stand. He only testified that he had called Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018 at 12:40:20pm to tell her that he had withdrawn the Money and Catherine Seah then requested him to open a UOB account[note: 53]. The accused failed to tell the court that it was during this telephone conversation that that he had arranged to meet her at 5pm at the Coffeeshop. Furthermore, as I would examine later, the messages after the 12:40:20pm call did not bear out the accused’s last-minute submission that it was during this call that the venue was changed to the Coffeeshop. The subsequent messages related to police investigations and the accused’s bank account being frozen which carried a different implication which I would deal with separately.

60     For the above reasons, I found that there was no arrangement on 5 October 2018 between the accused and Catherine Seah to meet at 5pm at the Coffeeshop.

The messages after the 12:40:20pm call on 5 October 2018 up to 10 October 2018 corroborated Catherine’s Seah’s evidence that the accused had failed to hand over the Money

(1)   Messages on 5 October 2018 after the 12:40:20pm call

61     According to the accused, he became suspicious when Catherine Seah requested him during the 12:40:20pm call to open a UOB bank account because Harry was going to transfer another $80,000 through his UOB account. That was why he lied to her to that his account, referring to his UOB account, was frozen and that was how the messages regarding the freezing of his account arose. He admitted that he did not have an existing UOB account. He said that although he was a discharged bankrupt, he still had outstanding loans with UOB so he would not be able to open an account with UOB.

62     I noted that after the 12:40:20pm call on 5 October 2018, there was a call from Harry Cheng to Catherine Seah at 12:47:40pm on 5 October 2018 and they spoke for one min and 48 seconds. In this regard, we would remember that only Catherine Seah’s call logs (exhibit P13) were produced in court and not her WhatsApp messages. Hence, we would not know whether she and Harry Cheng had exchanged any messages before Harry Cheng called her at 12:47:40pm. In any event, there was a marked difference in the tenor of the messages between Catherine Seah and the accused after these two phone calls. Prior to the 12:40:20pm call from the accused, the messages revolved around how soon the accused could withdraw the Money and give it to Catherine Seah at the Dialysis Centre. After her telephone conversation with the accused and Harry Cheng, instead of hastening the accused to withdraw the Money and bring it to the Dialysis Centre, Catherine Seah’s first message at 12:59:13pm was, “if it is under investigation by police, they will call u to go for interview”. She even asked the accused if Harry had called him and stated that “he don’t believed your account is freezed. that’s why i ask you if u need me to go to the bank with u”. The accused replied, “You also cannot help me. . Bank don’t entertain”.

63     The messages between Catherine Seah and the accused after the 12:40:20pm call have been set out at [55] above. The last message between them was at 1:48:33pm followed by hours of silence until 8:07:52pm when Catherine Seah messaged the accused to tell him that the person who deposited the sum of $20,000 into his POSB account may be making a police report to recall the Money otherwise Catherine Seah herself may have to lodge the police report. I noted that the messages on 5 October 2018 after 8:07pm were as follows:

64     Having regard to the messages following the 12:40:20pm call, I did not believe the accused’s evidence that he had told Catherine Seah during the 12:40:20pm call that he had withdrawn the Money and that his UOB account was frozen. A more plausible explanation would be that he had told Catherine Seah during the 12:40:20pm call that he was unable to withdraw the Money because his POSB account had been frozen. Only then would the subsequent messages on 5 October 2018 make sense.

65     Furthermore, it was odd for the accused to suddenly find it suspicious that Harry Cheng was planning to transfer more funds through his bank account. A perusal of the messages exchanged between the accused and Catherine Seah dating from September 2018 would reveal that the accused had assisted Catherine Seah with her monetary transactions previously. On 6 September 2018, Catherine Seah told the accused that she had lost her IC and asked if he could help her to send money to her husband’s friend (in Thailand) using the accused’s name and IC. The accused agreed and the transaction apparently took place on 7 September 2018.

66     I reproduce below the relevant messages between the accused and Catherine Seah prior to 4 October 2018 which would show that the accused was no stranger to requests from Catherine Seah to participate in her monetary matters or deals involving godpa Harry Cheng. As evident from the messages, the accused was aware that Catherine Seah had been summoned to the police station because someone had deposited money into her bank account by mistake which resulted in her bank account being frozen for investigations.

67     From the messages above, there was clearly no reason for the accused to turn distrustful of Harry Cheng or Catherine Seah out of the blue when he had recently helped Catherine Seah transfer money and had been in discussions with Catherine Seah to receive funds from Harry Cheng and transfer them on Harry Cheng’s behalf.

68     In my view, the accused made up the story that he felt suspicious upon learning that Harry Cheng was planning to transfer more funds through his UOB account which was why he then lied to Catherine Seah that his UOB account was frozen. In effect, he was trying to cover up the fact that he had told Catherine Seah during the 12:40:20pm that his POSB account was frozen to justify why he was unable to withdraw the Money to pass it to her as arranged. He embellished his tale to Catherine Seah by saying his POSB account was frozen due to suspected money laundering. He even pretended to be upset with Catherine Seah and worried that he was thereby dragged into trouble with the police[note: 54].

69     On 5 October 2018 at 1:14:36pm, the accused had messaged Catherine Seah to say that he was “Now at UOB” (reproduced at [55] above]). This was the first time on 5 October 2018 that “UOB” was specifically referred to in the messages. By then the accused and Catherine Seah had already started arguing about the accused’s frozen account three minutes earlier at 1:11:40pm. Considering all the messages exchanged on 5 October 2018, I believed that the accused brought up UOB in another context and not how he had testified.

(2)   Messages on 6 October 2018 up to 3:54:38pm

70     The messages between the accused and Catherine Seah on 6 October 2018 up to 3:54:38pm further proved that that the accused was referring to his POSB account being frozen because Catherine Seah was asking the accused to obtain a Statement of Account as godpa wanted to see if the sum of $20,000 had gone into his account, clearly referring to the accused’s POSB account. I agreed with the Prosecution that there was no reason for Catherine Seah to request the accused for proof that the Money was still in his account if he had already handed it to her the previous day on 5 October 2018[note: 55]. The accused expressed no surprise either at her request. I agreed with the Prosecution that he evaded her request by replying that he could not access his account because it was “locked” and “freezed already”[note: 56]. I also agreed with the Prosecution’s submissions at [23] and [26] to [32] of its Closing Submissions.

(3)   Messages on 6 October 2018 after 3:54:38pm to 7 October 2018

72     The subsequent messages on 6 October 2018 after 3:54:38pm also substantiated Catherine Seah’s evidence that the accused had failed to pass her the Money on 5 October 2018. Catherine Seah was clearly questioning the accused about the whereabouts of the Money and directly pointing her finger at him for withdrawing the Money and not giving it to her. During his cross-examination, the accused acknowledged that Catherine Seah had claimed that she did not receive the Money from him and for that reason he was angry with her for lying[note: 57]. Notwithstanding his proclaimed anger, it was telling that the accused not once clarify or deny her alleged false accusation or state that he had given her the Money. Instead, he replied “Freeze”. In my view, the reason why the accused did not refute Catherine Seah’s allegation was because it was true that he had not passed her the Money. For easy reference, I set out the relevant messages on 6 October 2018 below.

73     As set out in the table above, Catherine Seah even quoted Tan Choo’s messages to the accused where Tan Choo expressed suspicion that the accused had withdrawn the Money but lied about his account being frozen. I noted from Catherine Seah’s call log in exhibit P13 that she added Tan Choo as a new contact under a foreign number “+61 XXX” on 6 October 2018 at 9:19:19pm[note: 58]. In this regard, it was significant that on 7 October 2018, Tan Choo messaged the accused directly through WhatsApp and levelled similar accusations against the accused for withdrawing the Money yet not giving it to Catherine Seah. I set out below the messages sent by Catherine Seah and Tan Choo to the accused on 7 October 2018. Tan Choo’s messages to the accused were retrieved from the accused’s handphone.

74     The accused told the court that he did not reply to Tan Choo’s messages because he did not know the person. However, he did not attempt to clarify with Catherine Seah either as to why Tan Choo was still asking him to give the Money to her when he had already passed her the Money. In my view, similarly, the accused did not take any action on Tan Choo’s messages to him because it was correct that he had not passed her the Money.

(4)   Messages on 8 October to 10 October 2018

75     After 7 October 2018, the messages between Catherine Seah and the accused gradually tapered off. They exchanged a few messages on 8 October 2018 and 10 October 2018. It appeared that they ceased all contact thereafter. In this regard, we would recall that Catherine Seah lodged her police report in exhibit P3 against the accused on 7 October 2018 at 1:36pm and she gave her statement to the police in exhibit P5 on 11 October 2018 at 4pm. In Catherine Seah and Tan Choo’s final messages to the accused as captured in exhibit P9, Annex B on 8 and 10 October 2018, they both continued to press the accused to refund the Money, proving that the accused had not given the Money to Catherine Seah as arranged. Catherine Seah also called out the accused for lying.

76     For easy reference, the messages that Tan Choo sent to the accused on 8 October 2018 and the messages and call log between Catherine Seah and the accused on 8 and 10 October 2018 are re-produced below in two separate tables according to the dates. For completeness, I have reflected in the table the phone call which the victim PW2 Jessica Lee made to the accused on 10 October 2018 at 4:59:05pm. I will discuss PW2 Jessica Lee’s phone call to the accused separately at [83] to [89] below.

Between 5 and 6 October 2018 Catherine Seah was still hopeful that the accused would hand the Money to her

77     The Defence argued that if the accused had not handed over the Money to Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018, Catherine Seah would have messaged the accused continuously regarding the Money. Yet between 5pm to 8pm on 5 October 2018, there were no messages from Catherine Seah. The Defence also pointed to the messages on 6 October 2018 whereby Catherine Seah had invited the accused to join her for Indian rojak and contended that the accused must have handed over the Money to Catherine Seah on 5 October 2018 otherwise Catherine Seah would not have remained friendly to the accused and still asked to meet up with him.

78     In respect of the silence from Catherine Seah between 5pm and 8pm on 5 October 2018, she had just finished her dialysis that afternoon. The accused knew that Catherine Seah would feel very tired after her dialysis[note: 59]. Understandably she needed to rest. She resumed messaging the accused at 8:07:52pm on 5 October 2018[note: 60].

79     As regards Catherine Seah’s invitation to the accused to join her for Indian rojak, the Prosecution submitted that this was part of Catherine Seah’s attempts between 4.46pm to 7.14pm on 6 October 2018 to get the accused to meet with her including offering to provide him dinner in the hope that he would pass her the Money, but the accused repeatedly rebuffed her efforts. The Prosecution highlighted that Catherine Seah’s call to the accused at 5.56pm went unanswered[note: 61].

80     I agreed with the Prosecution that on a close reading of the messages on 5 and 6 October 2018, Catherine Seah was trying her best to reach the accused to collect the Money since he had failed to turn up at the Dialysis Centre as agreed and had not produced proof that the Money was still in his POSB account. I also agreed with the Prosecution that Catherine Seah was plainly frustrated with the situation when she told the accused on 6 October at 4:46:38pm to stop being stubborn.

81     Finally, Catherine Seah abandoned all hope that the accused would hand her the Money. She proceeded to lodge a police report on 7 October 2018 at 1.36pm against the accused for disappearing with the Money.

82     The relevant messages are set out below.

While PW2 Jessica Lee had given inconsistent evidence, it related to immaterial aspects of the case

83     PW2 Jessica Lee told the court that she had deposited the Money into the accused’s POSB account on the instructions of her online boyfriend Allen YuWong that the account belonged to a US tax agent and that she was helping Allen YuWong to pay for his property tax. The Defence argued that the transaction was suspicious since the Money which was sent to a Singapore account could not be used to pay a USA tax liability. Further, PW2 Jessica Lee testified that she did not speak with the accused however the Defence pointed out that exhibit P9, Annex A, serial number 532 showed that she had called the accused on 10 October 2018 at 4:59:05pm and the call lasted one min and 20 seconds. When PW2 Jessica Lee was re-called to the witness stand and confronted with the accused’s call log, she insisted that she did not call the accused. At the same time, she said that she could not remember and could not explain why the call log reflected that she had called the accused and spoken to him on 10 October 2018 when she did not know the accused.

84     PW2 Jessica Lee was then called to the witness stand a third time. She told the court that she thought over why she was able to call the accused directly and went home to search through her documents[note: 62]. That was when she found a second police report that she had lodged on 9 October 2018 at 8.44pm (exhibit D1). She had told the police in exhibit D1 that her fiancé, Allen YuWong, had engaged a lawyer who obtained the details of the person whom she transferred her sum of $20,000 to. The information she provided in her police report exhibit D1 included the accused’s name, IC number, phone number and address. This time round, based on the call log, she did not deny that she must have called the accused the next day on 10 October 2018 after lodging the police report in exhibit D1[note: 63]. However, as she could not recall the voice that she spoke to, she was not sure if it was the accused that she spoke to and she also could not remember the conversation[note: 64] although it was likely that she would have asked him for her money back[note: 65].

85     Given the suspicious nature of the transaction, inconsistencies in PW2 Jessica Lee’s evidence and her evasiveness during cross-examination, the Defence submitted that her evidence was unreliable and ought not to be accepted as truth. The Defence also highlighted that PW2 Jessica Lee was still in contact with Allen YuWong whose identity remained a mystery.

86     The Prosecution conceded that the nature of the transaction was suspicious. PW9 IO SSgt Zulkifli had testified that his investigations showed that PW2 Jessica Lee was the victim of an online scam who had been conned by Allen YuWong into believing that the accused was a tax officer and that transferring the Money into the accused’s account would assist Allen YuWong with his tax liabilities[note: 66]. It submitted that considering two years had lapsed since PW2 Jessica Lee lodged the police report in exhibit D1, it was not unusual that she could not recall having made a phone call to the accused or having lodged a second police report where she furnished the accused’s number. While the Prosecution recognized that it was impossible for Allen YuWong to have acquired the personal information of the accused through lawyer, it urged the court to note that PW2 Jessica Lee was merely reporting in exhibit D1 the details as she was told by Allen YuWong.

87     I agreed that it was dubious as to why PW2 Jessica Lee had to transfer the Money into the accused’s POSB account. I was also cognizant that PW2 Jessica Lee had been inconsistent in her evidence particularly as to whether she had spoken to the accused previously. Notwithstanding these reservations, what was important was that the crucial aspects of her evidence were not disputed. Insofar as the charge concerned PW2 Jessica Lee, the Prosecution was only required to establish that the Money belonged to PW2 Jessica Lee and that she had transferred it into the accused’s POSB account.

88     PW2 Jessica Lee had testified that she had deposited the Money which was her own money into the accused’s POSB account. Although PW2 Jessica Lee was not asked to produce the deposit receipt, she told the court that she had the receipt. The Defence did not challenge her evidence that the Money belonged to her. In any event, I agreed with the Prosecution that it was not the case of the Defence that the Money belonged to someone else or that it was the accused’s legitimate entitlement[note: 67]. In fact, the Defence confirmed expressly that it was not disputing that the accused received $20,000 on 4 October 2018, which was transferred into his account from PW2 Jessica Lee[note: 68].

89     I agreed with the Prosecution that since the two key facts were not in dispute, namely that the Money belonged to PW2 Jessica Lee and that she had transferred it into the accused’s account, the other contentions raised by the Defence were therefore immaterial and irrelevant. It was inconsequential that PW2 Jessica Lee had been inconsistent in her evidence on whether she had called and spoken with the accused.

Catherine Seah had no reason to falsely implicate the accused

90     I agreed with the Prosecution that Catherine Seah had no reason to falsely implicate the accused. I reproduce below the cogent submissions of the Prosecution in this regard.

41    Catherine had no incentive to falsely implicate the accused, and to lie that she had not received the [Money] if she had. By the accused’s own admission, although he was merely Catherine’s regular Ryde driver, Catherine treated the accused as a “godson”. Catherine’s affection for the accused is clear from the messages she exchanged with him. She gave him advice on his relationships and offered to set him up with a nurse at her dialysis centre. She asked him about his first marriage and children. She expressed concern over his health and how hard he worked, and even cooked for him on occasion. The two had meals together and the accused shared his personal problems with her. At no point is there any suggestion of any enmity that would cause Catherine to put such a serious charge on the accused.

42    Notably, even the accused agreed that Catherine had no reason to falsely implicate him. However, he went on to suggest that perhaps she lodged the police report to avoid being charged for money laundering. This claim is patently illogical. As seen by her statement, Catherine was fully aware that she had previously been warned for money laundering in relation to her dealings with Harry and knew that her actions carried grave consequences. Catherine had every incentive to keep her dealings with Harry (and by extension, the accused) a secret. Had the accused given her the [Money] as promised, there was no reason for Catherine to go to the police and risk being charged, or risk her lover Harry being charged.

43    By lodging the police report against the accused, not only had Catherine failed to keep herself out of trouble, Catherine had implicated herself, as she had brought police attention to the fact that she was dealing with an online entity with which she was expressly warned not to continue dealing with. In fact, if not for her death, Catherine would have been charged for money laundering offences. The fact that Catherine chose to lodge the police report against her own interests only increases, and does not diminish, her credibility.

The accused had the motive to commit criminal misappropriation

91     The accused did not deny that Catherine Seah being his godmother had been kind and generous with him. He told the court that she not only paid for his meals, but there were also times when Catherine Seah paid for his car rental expenses and petrol bills[note: 69]. The accused would readily approach Catherine Seah with his financial problems in the hope that she would help him out or buy the things for him. To give an example, he messaged her on 12 September 2018 to say, “Now very stressful … No $$$$$ ...How??? God mother ……”[note: 70]. In court, the accused claimed that he was hoping that she would buy health products for him.

92     In the weeks leading up to 4 October, I agreed with the Prosecution that it became increasingly clear that Catherine Seah was reluctant and unable to support the accused financially[note: 71]. This could be seen from her messages. On 22 September 2018 she reminded him that he had borrowed money from her which he had not repaid and that financially it was very difficult for her too[note: 72]. On 23 September 2018, when the accused again complained to Catherine Seah that he needed money for various reasons such as to pay his credit bills and housing rent and that he did not have enough money[note: 73], she told him that she needed her money back[note: 74]. At the same time, she chastised him for not saving his hard-earned money but thinking of spending money that he had not yet received[note: 75]. On 28 September 2018, Catherine Seah asked the accused when he would be able to return her the sum of $1,100[note: 76]. The accused told her, “End of October” to which Catherine Seah replied, “my goodness, i have not enough household money to u. please take care of your meal, i cant afford to buy for u any more.”[note: 77] The accused said “Ok” and that he would use his house cash proceeds to pay her.[note: 78]

93     The accused claimed that Catherine Seah was providing him “temporary support assistance” and he was only expected to repay her when he had the money[note: 79]. His assertion was however contradicted by the September 2018 messages where Catherine Seah was openly asking him to return the money which she had lent him and telling him frankly that she could no longer afford to foot for his meals and expenses. It would also be evident that the accused was facing financial difficulties because he had trouble repaying Catherine Seah’s loan and had been telling Catherine Seah that he did not have money and needed money. Hence, I agreed with the Prosecution that the accused had the motive and every incentive to dishonestly retain the Money when he was presented with the unexpected windfall of $20,000.

The accused’s failure to tell Catherine Seah that he had made partial withdrawal of the Money suggested a dishonest intent

94     The accused had made partial withdrawal of $5,000 on 4 October 2018 and he withdrew the balance of $15,000 on 5 October 2018 (see [25] above). There was no evidence before the court as to the timings of these withdrawals in particular the ones on 5 October 2018. Hence, it was unclear at what time on 5 October 2018 that the accused had withdrawn the full amount. What was clear was that the accused knew that Catherine Seah was waiting impatiently for the Money, yet he failed to tell her at any point in time that he had withdrawn $5,000 on 4 October 2018 and would be withdrawing the remainder on 5 October 2018.

95     In fact, when Catherine Seah asked him specifically on 5 October 2018 at 11:31:07am, “withdraw already?”[note: 80], he had replied “No”[note: 81]. Catherine Seah asked the accused a second time on 5 October 2018 at 11:54:57am to let her know when he had withdrawn the Money[note: 82]. Again, the accused did not disclose that he had withdrawn some of the Money. Instead, he told her he had just reached the bank[note: 83]. During his cross-examination, he explained that his job was to withdraw $20,000. Since he had only withdrawn $5,000 and not made full withdrawal, he did not think there was a need to tell Catherine Seah that he had withdrawn some of the Money[note: 84].

96     I did not believe the accused. He could have easily soothed his anxious godmother and told her the truth when she asked, that he had made partial withdrawal of the Money on 4 October 2018. I agreed with the Prosecution that his failure to do so suggested that he had the intent to conceal this fact. It was highly likely that the accused had formed the intention to dishonestly keep the Money for himself then.

The objective evidence proved that physically Catherine Seah could not have met the accused at 5pm at the Coffeeshop on 5 October 2018

97     The accused asserted that PW5 Lee Choon Hua, being one of Catherine Seah’s regular drivers, would have known that Catherine Seah would be waiting for him at the Dialysis Centre on 5 October 2018 from 4.15pm, and would have picked her up between 4.30 to 4.35pm thereby allowing her to reach Blk 494D at around 4.50pm so that she could meet up with the accused at the Coffeeshop at 5pm.

98     Either the accused was lying, or he was mistaken that PW5 Lee Choon Hua was Catherine Seah’s regular Ryde driver “Ah Hua”. Catherine Seah’s call log in exhibit P13 showed that she added PW5 Lee Choon Hua as a new contact on 5 October 2018 at 5.16pm, confirming PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence that he met Catherine Seah for the first time that day. As to whether it was true that Catherine Seah’s Ryde regular drivers had the habit of turning up at the Dialysis Centre earlier than the booking time, in this instance, it was irrelevant since PW5 Lee Choon Hua was not her regular driver.

99     Aside from PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence that he fetched Catherine Seah at around 4.50pm on 5 October 2018 and drop her off at 5.09pm at Blk 494D, the Prosecution also called one rebuttal witness PW10 Dolli Nitin Bisalappa (PW10 Dolli) to prove that physically Catherine Seah could have not met the accused at 5pm at the Coffeeshop.

100    Rebuttal witness PW10 Dolli was the Chief Technology Officer of Ryde. He started working for Ryde in January 2018. At the material time in October 2018, his position was that of a technical architect. He was familiar with the Ryde apps and their functions. He was the person responsible for the technological developments and features that Ryde released to its customers and all technical issues. He told the court that in October 2018, Ryde offered various services. In the present case, Catherine Seah booked its Ryde Pool service which was a service where the passenger might have to share his trip with another person if both persons were going on the same route or to the same destination. He said that there was no evidence that Catherine Seah had shared her trip with another passenger on 5 October 2018. In any event, it was not in dispute that Catherine Seah was PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s sole passenger for the trip.

101    PW10 Dolli explained that the Ryde passenger had two types of booking options, instantaneous booking, or advance booking of up to seven days. To make a booking, the passenger would have to click on the desired service, enter pick-up address, drop-off address and thereafter opt for real-time driver or advance booking. The fare would be displayed, and the passenger could then proceed with the booking. Contrary to what the accused told the court, PW10 Dolli confirmed that as of October 2018, both instantaneous and advance bookings were available.

102    PW10 Dolli testified when a passenger made an advance booking, it would appear on a job/trip list on the drivers’ side of the app where they could see all the nearby trips and the drivers could accept or decline the trip. Once a driver accepted a trip by clicking on the button, the app would send a notification to the passenger to inform the passenger that it had matched the passenger with a driver, and the app would start showing the real-time location of the driver to the passenger. Upon arrival at the pick-up location, the driver would have to click on “Trip Start” and upon reaching the destination, the driver would have to click on “Drop-off”. Ryde would pay the driver for the trip when the driver had clicked on “Drop-off” by crediting the fare into the driver’s wallet after deducting its commission of five per cent.

103    PW10 Dolli stated that Ryde tracked the whereabouts of the drivers on its platform by collecting their real-time locations from two sources. Each time the drivers performed any action on the Ryde app such as clicking on the “Accept Trip” button or “Start Trip” button, the time and location where the driver performed the action would be registered (“Action Data”). Ryde would also collect real-time location data of all its drivers through the app every seven seconds (“Real-Time Data”).

104    PW10 Dolli explained that exhibit P12 showed the Action Data and Real-Time Data of PW5 Lee Choon Hua on 5 October 2018 between 4pm and 6.30pm. During this time, PW5 Lee Choon Hua made three trips involving three different passengers. Page 2 of exhibit P12 summarized the trip taken by Catherine Seah (“trip summary”). The trip summary showed that Catherine Seah had made an advance booking for Ryde Pool at 3.54:11pm. She had indicated her pick-up time as 4.50pm from 105 Aljunied Crescent and her destination was Blk 494D. The trip summary reflected PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s Action Data. He had accepted the booking at 4.28:06pm. The Real-Time Data on page 4 of exhibit P12 showed that around that time, he was on Guillemard Road. At 4.35pm, it showed PW5 Lee Choon Hua as driving along Geylang East Central, and he only reached Aljunied Crescent around 4:49:19pm. Hence, based on exhibit P12, PW5 Lee Choon Hua could not have picked up Catherine Seah between 4.30pm to 4.35pm from the Dialysis Centre.

105    The Action Data showed that PW5 Lee Choon Hua “started” Catherine Seah’s trip at 4:49:23pm. Both the Action Data and Real-Time data showed that when PW5 Lee Choon Hua clicked on “Start Trip” at 4:49:19pm, he was already at Aljunied Crescent. The Real-Time Data showed that at 4:55:02pm, PW5 Choon Hua was driving along Paya Lebar Road. At 5:00:03pm, PW5 Choon Hua was driving along the PIE. At 5:05:04pm, PW5 Choon Hua had just driven into Tampines Avenue 2. Both the Action Data and Real-Time Data showed that at 5:09:35pm, PW5 Choon Hua arrived at Blk 494D where he clicked on the “Drop-off” button.

106    PW10 Dolli’s evidence and exhibit P12 thus materially corroborated PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s testimony that he had fetched Catherine Seah around 4.50pm from the Dialysis Centre and dropped her off at around 5.09pm. In this regard, I noted that PW5 Lee Choon Hua was somewhat confused as to whether Catherine Seah had made an advance booking or instantaneous booking. During cross-examination, he said that he “received” Catherine Seah’s call at about 4.50pm so he should have picked her at 4.51pm since he was nearby. He clarified that when he said he “received” her call at 4.50pm, he had meant that his phone rang indicating that there was a customer and he had gone into the app “to press” to accept the job. There was no actual phone call[note: 85]. PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence that he accepted Catherine Seah’s booking on the spot also suggested that she had made an instantaneous booking rather than an advance booking. From PW10 Dolli’s evidence and exhibit P12, this was clearly not the case because Catherine Seah had made an advance booking at 3.54:11pm.

107    When PW5 Lee Choon Hua came to court to testify as a witness, he was no longer working as a Ryde driver[note: 86]. He said that due to the passage of time, he had forgotten many details. He also did not have the benefit of exhibit P12 which was only tendered in court after he had given his evidence. Subsequently, when PW5 Lee Choon Hua was recalled to the witness stand and shown exhibit P12, he clarified that he could not recall if Catherine Seah’s booking was an advanced or instantaneous booking. In any event, PW5 Lee Choon Hua was firm that he could not have fetched Catherine Seah earlier than 4.50pm and fetched her home to Blk 494D at about 5pm.

108    Not only was PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence materially corroborated by PW10 Dolli and exhibit P12, Catherine Seah’s call log in exhibit P13 also substantiated his evidence that he had fetched Catherine Seah at around 4.50pm. The call log showed that Catherine Seah had two missed calls from PW5 Lee Choon Hua on 5 October 2018 at 4:46:26pm and 4:47:43pm. When PW5 Lee Choon Hua was recalled to the witness stand and shown exhibit P13, he explained that he had called Catherine Seah because he could not find her at the pick-up point[note: 87]. PW5 Lee Choon Hua had clearly called Catherine Seah to ascertain her whereabouts as he could not locate her initially. The Real-Time Data in P12 at page 4 showed that he was in the vicinity of 109 Aljunied Crescent and Aljunied Crescent between 4:45:43pm and 4:49;19pm. Therefore, he could not have fetched Catherine Seah from the Dialysis Centre at 4.30pm to 4.35pm. Catherine Seah’s call log further proved that PW5 Lee Choon Hua could not have fetched Catherine Seah earlier at 4.30pm or 4.35pm. If he had fetched her by then, he would have no reason to call her and twice for that matter.

109    For completeness, Catherine Seah’s call log in exhibit P13 showed that she had called PW5 Lee Choon Hua at 5:14:37pm on 5 October 2018 and the call lasted 14 seconds. I noted that she added him as a new contact at 5:16:17pm. In my view, Catherine Seah probably called PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s number when she saw that she had two missed calls earlier and she later saved his number for her future Ryde trips.

110    PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence that he had dropped Catherine Seah at Blk 494D at around 5.09pm was corroborated by his trip details in exhibit P4, and his Action Data and Real-Time Data in exhibit P12. He explained that he would have to “log off” immediately after Catherine Seah’s trip, otherwise he would not be able to fetch the next customer. Besides, he would only receive payment for the trip from Ryde after he had logged off. Hence, from the evidence adduced, PW5 Lee Choon Hua clearly did not reach Blk 494D earlier than 5pm as the Defence had claimed.

111    The objective evidence therefore proved that physically Catherine Seah could not have met the accused at 5pm at the Coffeeshop because PW5 Lee Choon Hua only fetched Catherine Seah at about 4.50pm at the Dialysis Centre and she alighted at Blk 494D at about 5.09pm. At 5pm, they were travelling along the PIE. Furthermore, the CCTV footage in exhibit P6 showed Catherine Seah arriving at her residential block at Blk 494E and entering the lift at 5.10pm and up until 8pm, she did not come down again. I agreed with the Prosecution that it was not possible for Catherine Seah who had just finished her dialysis to walk over to the Coffeeshop, collect the Money, walk back, and go up to her flat in less than a minute. Catherine Seah had simply gone straight home after the accused failed to turn up at the Dialysis Centre because he claimed that his POSB account was frozen and therefore he was unable to withdraw the Money.

112    For completeness, the trip details in exhibit P4 showed that the fare for Catherine Seah’s trip was $9. Ryde took $0.45 being 5% service fee/commission at that time and PW5 Lee Choon Hua earned $8.55. The trip details in exhibit P4 showed that Ryde credited $8.55 into PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s wallet at 5.09pm although administratively the driver could only cash out the payment at least seven days later.

113    To sum up, PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s evidence and the objective data from Ryde in exhibit P12 proved that physically Catherine Seah could not have met the accused at 5pm at the Coffeeshop on 5 October 2018 and passed her the Money.

Full weight ought to be given to Catherine Seah’s police report and statement

114    Although the late Catherine Seah could not be cross examined, and have her veracity tested, I was of the view that full weight ought to be attached to her police report and her statement. I noted that she had given differing versions as to the purpose of the Money. In her police report in exhibit P3, she stated that the Money was a loan from Tan Choo, Harry Cheng’s friend, for her medical expenses. In her statement in exhibit P5, she stated that Harry Cheng had borrowed the Money from his friends to pay for his daughter’s school expenses. I agreed with the Prosecution that the discrepancies were immaterial. What was critical and relevant was she had been clear and consistent that the accused did not hand her the Money. In this regard, her evidence was not only internally consistent in the material aspects, but it was also externally consistent with the messages that she had sent to the accused. She also had no reason to falsely implicate the accused (see [90] above).

The accused was not a credible witness

115    I did not find the accused to be a credible witness. First, his evidence was internally inconsistent. While he insisted that he subsequently arranged to meet Catherine Seah at the Coffeeshop at 5pm, the messages did not support his contentions. He failed to clarify or clear his name when Catherine Seah chased him for the Money and reproached him for withdrawing it and not giving it to her. His explanation that since he had passed her the Money, there was no need for him to state the obvious was illogical because the natural response would have been for him to tell her that he had given her the Money so why was she still pestering him for it. Externally, his evidence that he had met Catherine Seah at the Coffeeshop at 5pm was refuted by the evidence from PW5 Lee Choon Hua and PW10 Dolli as being factually impossible because she was travelling in PW5 Lee Choon Hua’s vehicle along the PIE at 5pm and only arrived at Blk 494D at 5.09pm. I therefore disbelieved his Defence.

Conclusion

116    In summary, the evidence showed that the accused was in financial difficulties and Catherine Seah had been kind to help him out. When he came into possession of the Money on 4 October 2018, he took the calculated chance to dishonestly misappropriate the Money because he thought that Catherine Seah was unlikely to report the matter to the police and risked exposing herself to criminal liability since the transaction smacked of money laundering. Unfortunately for him, Catherine Seah decided to go to the police. He then came up with the contrived account that his meeting place with Catherine Seah shifted from the Dialysis Centre to the Coffeeshop with his bare “See you at 5” message. He later tried to tweak the timings of Catherine Seah’s journey home from the Dialysis Centre on 5 October 2018 so that they would fit into his story.

117    On the totality of the evidence, I was satisfied beyond a reasonable doubt that the accused had dishonestly misappropriated the Money by withdrawing it for his own use.

Antecedents

118    The accused admitted to the following antecedents. I have highlighted the relevant ones.

Prescribed punishment

119    The prescribed punishment for dishonest misappropriation of property under s 403 of the Penal Code was imprisonment for a term which might extend to two years or with fine or with both.

Parties’ sentencing positions

120    The Prosecution submitted for a sentence of at least ten to 12 weeks’ imprisonment given the relatively high value of the Money misappropriated and the character of the accused. The Defence argued that a sentence of four weeks’ imprisonment would suffice.

Sentence imposed by the court

121    Deterrence would be the dominant sentencing consideration.

122    In sentencing the accused to ten weeks’ imprisonment, I took into account the following aggravating factors:

(a)     As a general principle, in sentencing offences under s 403 of Penal Code, the higher the quantum of money or value of property misappropriated, the heftier the sentence: Shaik Farid v PP and other appeals [2017] 5 SLR 1081 at [56]. In this case, the misappropriated sum of $20,000 was not an insignificant amount. Furthermore, there was no restitution.

(b)     There was pre-meditation involved. I agreed with the Prosecution that this was not a situation where the offender suddenly received unexpected windfalls in their bank accounts which they then misappropriated. The accused was expecting the Money to be deposited into his account pursuant to his arrangement with Catherine Seah. The accused not only formed the dishonest intention to misappropriate the Money, but he also came up with a plan to stall Catherine Seah by pretending that he had yet to withdraw the Money and was queuing at the bank when he had made partial withdrawal the night before. He eventually lied to her that he could not withdraw the Money because his POSB account was frozen.

(c)     The accused betrayed the trust of his godmother Catherine Seah who had been kind to him and thought that she could count on him to help her receive the substantial sum in his account and then withdrawing the Money to pass it to her.

(d)     It was aggravating that the accused had property antecedents. It was relevant to note that he was last sentenced to ten months’ imprisonment and fined $32,000 for criminal breach of trust as a servant in June 2011. Barely seven and a half years later, he went on to commit the present offence in October 2018. He had clearly not learned his lesson. Specific deterrence was thus warranted.

123    In mitigation, the learned counsel told the court that the accused suffered from various ailments such as diabetes and serious heart conditions. The learned counsel expressed concern as to whether the Prisons would be able to care for the accused’s medical needs. In this regard, Prisons had confirmed that they possessed the experience in dealing with inmates with a variety of medical conditions and had an adequate system of healthcare delivery in place to manage the accused’s medical conditions. Specifically, they had noted the accused’s medical history of diabetes with lower limb complications and heart conditions. Prisons gave the assurance that the accused would be assessed by their medical officer and necessary medical support would be provided to him. Hence, the accused had no cause for worry.

124    Aside from the accused’s medical conditions which were not mitigating, the Defence did not raise anything else that would constitute a mitigating factor.

125    For completeness, I will briefly discuss the precedents cited by the Prosecution. The Defence did not cite any. For easy reference, I reproduce below Prosecution’s table of precedents in respect of s 403 of the Penal Code.

MSC-902607-2019

Pleaded guilty

s 403 PC

The victim erroneously transferred various sums of money to the accused’s account. The accused was informed by HSBC that the monies were wrongfully transferred but withdrew $20,000 and dishonestly misappropriated it.

Accused made full restitution.

Untraced

PP v Neo Boon Seng

[2008] SGHC 90

Pleaded guilty

s 403 PC

Accused pleaded guilty to one charge under s 403 of the Penal Code. The accused was a taxi driver and the victim was his passenger. The victim had left items amounting to a total value of $11,661.05 in the front passenger seat. Instead of returning the items, the accused misappropriated them.

Items with an approximate total value of $4000.00 were not recovered. Accused did not make restitution for the value of the items not recovered.

Untraced

3 weeks’ imprisonment
