PP v Tan Cheng Hin

MAC-903453-2017 and Ors

Pleaded guilty

s 403 PC

Accused pleaded guilty to two charges, one under s 204A of the Penal Code and one under s 403 of the Penal Code. On 25 July 2016, complainant had brought a black bag containing his iPhone, various jewellery items, and a large amount of cash with a total value of S$77,777.87 to a coffee shop. He left the coffee shop without taking the bag. Accused noticed that the bag was left unattended and took it. He discovered that it contained a lot of money. From 26 July 2016, the accused began spending the money found in the complainant’s bag. He then used a portion of the money to repay debts. Separately, he took a holiday to Batam where he spent S$6,000 of the money found in the complainant’s bag. Most of the items were recovered. However, the total value not recovered was S$14,303.10.

No restitution was made for this amount.

Traced for unrelated antecedents

16 weeks’ imprisonment for the s 403 charge

6 weeks’ imprisonment for the s 204A charge

Both sentences ran concurrently

4

PP v Wong Chee Keong

MAC-904104- 2017

Pleaded guilty

s 403 PC

Accused pleaded guilty to one charge under s 403 of the Penal Code. Accused was working as a part-time Uber driver. Accused picked up the complainant and the complainant left a black coloured sling bag containing items (laptop, iPhone with casing, and cash) with a total value of S$21,717.65. The next day, the complainant realised that her sling bag was missing and tried contacting the accused but the latter claimed that there was nothing in his vehicle and informed the complainant that there were several passengers who had taken his vehicle after she alighted and he would check with them. After the complainant informed the accused that she had made a police report, the accused claimed that he had found a large amount of cash and returned the cash to the complainant. The laptop was eventually recovered.

The accused made full restitution of S$1,300.00 to the complainant for the items (iPhone with casing) that were not returned to the complainant.

Traced for theft in 2000

4 weeks’ imprisonment

5

Krishan Chand v PP [1995] 1 SLR(R) 737

s 403 PC

Plead Guilty

Cited in Sentencing Practice in the Subordinate Courts book

The accused, 63 years old, pleaded guilty to one charge under s 403, Penal Code (Cap 224) and another charge under s 406(a), Companies Act (Cap 50). The accused was an officer of a company and had dishonestly induced a Bank to grant a term of overdraft of $200,000 to the company, by relying on a sum of US$301,013.88 which was credited to the company in error. This formed the basis for the Companies Act offence. For the s 403, Cap 224 charge, the accused instructed the bank to close the fixed deposit account and over 2 occasions, asked the company to credit the monies into the company’s current account. He then proceeded to withdraw $120,000 from the current account.

Full restitution effected.

Untraced

On appeal, sentence reduced to 6 months’ imprisonment each and both sentences to run concurrently.

Total sentence: 6 months’ imprisonment



126    The Defence relied on the fourth precedent in PP v Wong Chee Keong (“Wong”) where Wong who was traced for theft was sentenced to four weeks’ imprisonment for misappropriating $21,717.65 to argue that the accused should be sentenced to four weeks’ imprisonment for misappropriating $20,000.

127    There were no grounds of decision issued for Wong’s case. Be that as it may, Wong pleaded guilty unlike the accused who claimed trial and therefore was not entitled to any sentencing discount. Furthermore, Wong made full restitution of S$1,300 for the items which were not recovered. In the present case, there was no restitution.

128    Having regard to the precedents and the aggravating factors set out above, I was of the view that an appropriate sentence was ten weeks’ imprisonment which I imposed accordingly.

129    The accused is presently on bail pending appeal.
